"The only thing that separates women of color from anyone else is opportunity," Davis said in <a href="http://www.ew.com/article/2015/09/20/emmys-2015-viola-davis-acceptance-speech" target="_blank">her speech</a> Sunday night after becoming the first African-American woman to win an Emmy in the lead actress drama category.

Davis isn't just talking about leaning in but inviting us all in. She not only spoke for black women but her words resonated with Latinas, Asian American and Native American women.

What Davis said goes beyond Hollywood. I can relate.

I've applied for jobs in the tech industry. I've tried to break into book publishing. I've tried to rise in the ranks at  newspapers.

And the doors have been shut on me and many other people like me. Those who make it through are few.

I have more than 20 years experience in journalism, more than a decade teaching everything from digital media to immigration reporting, and a Master of Fine Arts in Creative Writing.

So what's wrong?

It could be that I don't have the experience. But I honestly don't believe that.

Davis is right. It's about having the opportunity.

The statistics tell a grim story.

In Hollywood, only six of the top 500 top grossing films of all time feature a woman of color, according to <a href="http://mic.com/articles/84899/hollywood-s-problem-with-women-of-color-is-even-worse-than-you-realize" target="_blank">the Representation Project</a>. And five of them were animated films, including "Pocahontas" and "The Princess and the Frog." The only live action film on that list is" Sister Act" starring Whoopi Goldberg and that came out in 1992.

In the tech industry, according to <a href=" http://www.theverge.com/2015/8/20/9179853/tech-diversity-scorecard-apple-google-microsoft-facebook-intel-twitter-amazon" target="_blank">Verge</a>, Twitter has so few black women working there that they are statistically zero percent. Black women are 1 percent at Google, Facebook and Microsoft. Latinas are 1 percent of employees at Twitter, Google and Microsoft and 2 percent at Facebook. White women average 16 percent and Asian women 6 percent of employees at tech companies.

In academia, according to <a href="http://www.catalyst.org/knowledge/women-academia" target="_blank">Catalyst</a>, Asian women held 4.8 percent of tenure-track positions and 2.6 percent  of tenured positions. Black women held 3.7 percent  of tenure-track positions and 2.2  percent  of tenured positions. Hispanic women held 2.5 percent  of tenure-track positions and 2.3 percent of tenured positions.

In this case I am an exception and among the 2.3 percent of Latina professors with tenure.

And even when we do get jobs we are paid less. According to <a href="http://www.aauw.org/2014/09/18/gender-pay-gap/" target="_blank">AAUW</a>, Black women earn 64 percent of what white men earn and Latinas 54 percent compared to 78 percent for white women. Asian women have the smallest pay gap and make 90 percent of what men make.

Native American women are not even ranked in most of the data.

I don't think women of color are asking for any special treatment. We just want to be invited to the table.

Let's be honest. This is what white men do for each other all the time.

How else do you explain Stephen Colbert?

Colbert reportedly has an <a href="http://splitsider.com/2015/09/17-men-2-women-colberts-writers-room-shows-that-nothings-changed-in-late-night/" target="_blank">all white writing staff</a>, 17 men and two women. And no people of color.

And if we really want not just Hollywood but the world to change than we need people in positions of power to shift their thinking.
It's not only about reflecting the changing demographics of America. It's also about acknowledging that  communities of color have spending power amounting to more than a trillion dollars each for <a href="http://www.blackenterprise.com/small-business/african-american-buying-power-projected-trillions/" target="_blank">blacks</a> and <a href="http://www.statista.com/statistics/251438/hispanics-buying-power-in-the-us/" target="_blank">Hispanics</a>.

So give us the opportunity to help you better reflect America and everyone will profit.";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Teresa Puente";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4345:"Viola Davis struck a chord with women of color across the U.S. who often feel invisible or ignored.

